Both Roizen and Willett recommend cosmuning the aforementioned D-laced foods whenever possible, but point to pills as your safest bet to amp up D levels. ‚ÄúVitamin D3 is created in the body and activated by the sun or added to foods, but it‚Äôs also the same version you get from supplements,‚Äù explains Roizen. So, while research is ongoing on as to the clear amount of D we should each strive for, ‚ÄúI think it makes sense for most people to take 1000 or 2000 IU‚Äôs of vitamin D per day as a supplement,‚Äù says Willet who suspects we‚Äôll eventually being seeing modified vitamin D recommendations as scientific evidence accumulates. ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs a strong suggestion that people with darker skin may even need up to 4000 IU‚Äôs per day,‚Äù he says.And a little insider tip: ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs data that shows taking vitamin D with a fat like DHA, omega-3, or just have a little olive oil and bread with it, absorbs better,‚Äù notes Roizen.
